# Workflow and Quality Rules

- Before making changes, inspect the relevant files instead of assuming framework defaults.
- Prefer small, targeted edits that fit the current codebase.
- Avoid adding new dependencies unless the benefit is clear and project-specific.

## When changing behavior

- Update docs if the behavior, route structure, startup flow, or deployment assumptions change.
- Preserve existing user-facing patterns unless the task explicitly asks for redesign.
- Call out mismatches between docs and implementation rather than silently ignoring them.
- For any routing change, update `README.md` in the same change set.

## Validation

- After non-trivial code changes, run the relevant checks when possible:
  - `npm run lint`
  - `npm run build`
- Any change touching recharge or withdraw flows must run both `npm run lint` and `npm run build` before completion.
- Recharge or withdraw flow changes include work in:
  - `src/views/RechargeView.vue`
  - `src/views/WithdrawView.vue`
  - `src/views/BusinessRechargeView.vue`
  - `src/stores/recharge.js`
  - `src/stores/withdraw.js`
  - `src/api/modules/topup/recharge.api.js`
  - `src/api/modules/topup/withdraw.api.js`
- If a check cannot be run, say so explicitly.

## Code review mindset

- Watch for:
  - auth regressions
  - broken route guards
  - duplicated state
  - missing loading or error handling
  - UI inconsistencies across mobile screens
  - money or order-state formatting mistakes

## Scope control

- Do not rewrite large parts of the app when a smaller fix is enough.
- If the task touches only one screen, keep unrelated files stable unless they must change.
